         <abstract>
            <p>In order to study the density of the set of positive integers d for which the negative Pell equation x<sup>2</sup> - dy<sup>2</sup> = -1 is solvable in integers, we compute the norm of the fundamental unit in certain well-chosen families of real quadratic orders. A fast algorithm that computes 2-class groups rather than units is used. It is random polynomial-time in log d as the factorization of d is a natural part of the input for the values of d we encounter. The data obtained provide convincing numerical evidence for the density heuristics for the negative Pell equation proposed by the second author. In particular, an irrational proportion P = 1 - Π<sub>j ≥ 1 odd</sub>(1 - 2<sup>-j</sup>) ≈ .58 of the real quadratic fields without discriminantal prime divisors congruent to 3 mod 4 should have a fundamental unit of norm -1.</p>
          </abstract>
